{
  "doc_id": "48250",
  "text": "In our study, the preliminary tests with meat product prototypes consisted of tannin extracts with concentrations of 0.1% and 1% in the products by using both dried and liquid type extracts. The male panelists did not seem to find the level of astringency and bitterness too high as they preferred the taste of higher concentration over the lower extract concentration. For women in contrast, the preferred extract concentration was the lower one. Several studies have examined the relationship between wine or grape extract polyphenol/PAs sensory properties and their structure [CITATION_1] [CITATION_2] [CITATION_3] [CITATION_4] . Whereas it is clear that the perception of astringency increases with tannin concentration on a mass basis and with increasing molecular size, i.e., DP, detailed and convergent information about particular sub attributes is still lacking [CITATION_5] . Peleg et al. [CITATION_6] compared the bitterness and astringency of aqueous solutions of (+)-catechin and (-)-epicatechin monomers and their five synthetic oligomers (three dimers and two trimers). They noted, as well, that as the molecular size increased the bitterness decreased and astringency increased [CITATION_7] .",
